CatDescriptText: Mrs. Alice Dunn, housewife, 7206 Race Street., was part of the "Pittsburghers Speak Up" column published in Pittsburgh Courier newspaper, October 10, 1959, pg. A1, with question: "How do you think Soviet Premier Khrushchev's visit to the United States affected relations between our country and Russia? Were you or were you not impressed by his visit to Pittsburgh?" answer reads: "I think the visit was a wonderful move and it would be wise for President Eisenhower to return the visit.  I think that the visit helped to resolve a lot of doubts, or rather I should say if the doubts are not completely resolved, they are partially resolved.  I was very much impressed by the reception which Pittsburghers gave him."
TitMainTitle: Portrait of Alice Dunn, wearing plaid dress, light colored button earrings, and necklace of three strands of pearls or beads, standing on Liberty Avenue in front of the Empire Building, Downtown
